Whether BBI is good and should be adapted, or it is bad and should be discarded, depends largely on the gaze through which one views it.
“Haven’t you read the BBI? It solves all the problems that we are experiencing. Imagine a tax holiday!” Kimani mentioned the mouth-watering promises that he had read in the BBI.
Danger of a single story
“You read it selectively, and that is how you are falling onto the trap and danger of a single, biased story,” Wajohi said sensibly. “Have you considered where you will get a job to raise money to start repaying your HELB after the break? There are no jobs.” Kimani was being a rationalist and a realist. But as the referee, my duty was to remain impartial and objective. But I can assure you it was not an easy task. I was being tossed from one side to the other, at least by ideas, not political strengths and that was a consolation.
“The BBI will create jobs. Or you can employ yourself,” Kimani said with a sense of defeat. He could not defend the ideas stipulated in the BBI for the benefit of Wanjiku.
“That is political talk,” Wajohi said. “A document has never created any jobs. It is as good as if it did not exist, if in the first place the implementers don’t care. After all, it is every man for himself, and God for us all,” Wajohi said.



